  "texts": [
    "Conversely, lower surprise values suggest closer alignment between expectations and observations.",
    "This equation denotes that surprise is a value that can be modeled, allowing for possible prediction of hunch generation and severity.",
    "A hunch is not something that is ephemeral, it is the outcome of underlying Bayesian processing, and the generation of a world model that seek to actively infer and manage the presenting 'level' of surprise.",
    "This is known as Bayesian belief updating, where prior beliefs about (unobservable) causes are updated into posterior beliefs after seeing (observable) consequences.",
    "For example, seeing a distressed woman outside her house (observable consequences) revises prior beliefs about domestic abuse (unobservable causes)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}